note_en:
SDLang is a simple and concise way to textually represent data. It has an XML-like structure – tags, values and attributes – which makes it a versatile choice for data serialization, configuration files, or declarative languages. Its syntax was inspired by the C family of languages (C/C++, C#, D, Java, …).
 // This is a node with a single string value   &#34;Hello, World&#34; // Multiple values are supported, too   12 15 188 1234 // Nodes can have attributes   &#34;Peter Parker&#34;  email= &#34;peter@example.org&#34;  active= true // Nodes can be arbitrarily nested  {	   &#34;First section&#34; {		   &#34;This is the first paragraph&#34;		   &#34;This is the second paragraph&#34;	}} // Anonymous nodes are supported &#34;This text is the value of an anonymous node!&#34; // This makes things like matrix definitions very convenient  {	 1 0 0	 0 1 0	 0 0 1}
          // Strings &#34;String \&#34;with escape support\&#34;&#34; `String &#34;without escape support&#34;` // Numbers 10   // 32-bit integer 10L   // 64-bit integer 10.5   // 64-bit float (double) 10.5d  // 64-bit float 10.5f  // 32-bit float 10.123BD   // 128-bit decimal // Boolean and null values true   // boolean true false  // boolean false on   // boolean true off   // boolean false null   // a null value // Date/time formats 2015/12/06 12:00:00.000-UTC  // Date/time value (UTC timezone) 2015/12/06 12:00:00.000   // Date/time value (local time) 2015/12/06   // Date value 12:14:34   // Duration: 12 hours, 14 minutes, 34 seconds 12:14:34.123  // 12 h, 14 min, 34 s, 123 ms 2d:12:14:34   // 2 days, 12 h, 14 min, 34 s // Binary data (Base64 encoded) [sdf789GSfsb2+3324sf2]
